texts.html: Ask Dr. Sher A Question

All women who undergo embryo transfer (ET) are focused on having a healthy baby. The truth is that fewer than 40% will succeed after a single attempt. And when they fail, the questions that follow will be ….Why did I not succeed?  Should I try again?  What can we do differently next time around to prevent repeat failure?  In most cases, the treating physician will not be able to satisfactorily and with confidence answer such questions. This is because of a relative inability to differentiate between an implantation dysfunction (anatomical or immunologic) and an embryo defect as being the problem, and whether (in the case of the latter) a sperm or an egg issue was involved.  There is no doubt an urgent need for the treating physician to be able to address such concerns upfront, before initiating any IVF cycle of treatment, whether an initial or a repeat attempt.

texts.html: It is a fact that the numerical chromosomal integrity (karyotype) of the embryo is one of the most important factors that determines IVF outcome, and that it is largely chromosomal integrity of the egg rather than the sperm that determines the integrity of the embryo karyotype. In fact, abnormal embryo karyotype (aneuploidy) is believed to be responsible for >70% both of IVF failures and miscarriages, and also for many birth defects such as Down syndrome, Turner’s syndrome, etc.

texts.html: While microscopic embryo morphologic assessment can in some cases identify those embryos that are structurally defective, they would be highly unlikely to propagate healthy offspring (i.e. “incompetent”). It is also indisputable that morphologically normal looking embryos are often aneuploid and thus, “incompetent,” so microscopic assessment of competency is unreliable.  While slightly less than 50% of embryos derived through fertilization of the eggs of a woman in her early 30’s are likely to be chromosomally normal (euploid), this declines ever more rapidly as she reaches her late 30’s. By the time she reaches her mid-40’s, less than 1 in 10 of her eggs/embryos are likely to be euploid. The truth is that without genetic assessment to confirm the presence of all 23 chromosome pairs, it is impossible to reliably affirm embryo competence.

texts.html: Hindsight embryo karyotyping (HSK) is a genetic testing process in which ALL embryos created in the IVF cycle are biopsied to remove several cells from each embryo prior to transfer. The biopsied cells are cryopreserved in the eventuality that the IVF cycle is unsuccessful or for subsequent testing for other reasons. Because each embryo is tracked separately, the biopsied cells can be sent for genetic testing to evaluate whether there was a chromosomal issue responsible for IVF failure.

texts.html: The process is this: the woman is stimulated and monitored as normal. The egg retrieval is performed, the eggs are prepared and fertilized by intracytoplasmic sperm injection (ICSI), and then cultured for 3 days. At this point, a biopsy is performed on each embryo, and several cells (blastomeres) are removed The biopsied blastomeres are then frozen and stored while the embryos are allowed to continue in culture for an additional 2-3 days. At this time, we transfer one or two expanded, morphologically sound to the uterus. The remainder (supernumerary blastocysts) are frozen for use in a subsequent cycle, at the sole discretion of the woman/couple.

texts.html: Comparative Genomic Hybridization (CGH): The last decade witnessed the introduction of tests such as CGH which fully karyotype embryos. This resulted in a new-found ability to choose only the most “competent” embryos for selective transfer and, in the process, vastly improve the efficiency of IVF as well as outcome.  But CGH (whether array or metaphase) as well as most other chromosomal embryo karyotyping methods currently in use for embryo karyotyping, are far from being devoid of problems. They all tend to be associated with “false positive” results, some of which are due to the unavoidable occurrence of “embryo mosaicism” (which in many cases will “auto-correct”), and others that are due to “noise” in the analytic recordings that all too often falsely points to an erroneous increase or decrease in chromosomal material, thereby confounding accurate interpretation of results.

texts.html: Next Generation Gene Sequencing (NGS):Next Generation Gene Sequencing (NGS): Gene sequencing determines the precise order of nucleotides within a DNA molecule. It includes any method or technology that is used to determine the order of the four bases—adenine, guanine, cytosine, and thymine—in a strand of DNA. A new generation of sequencing technologies (also called next generation gene sequencing) has provided unprecedented opportunities for high-throughput functional genomic research. To date, these technologies have been applied in a variety of contexts, including full karyotyping of embryos), targeted re-sequencing, discovery of transcription factor binding sites, and non-coding RNA expression profiling. NGS, as performed to identify human embryo aneuploidy, is in our opinion is likely to be at least as reliable as metaphase CGH (mCGH) and more reliable than array CGH (aCGH). As is the case with mCGH (and unlike with aCGH) NGS can be conducted reliably on single blastomeres (derived from day 2-3, cleaved embryos). When performed on more than one blastocyst (trophectoderm) cell NGS can help differentiate between meiotic and mitotic aneuploidy. This has potential advantages because unlike meiotic aneuploidy which is permanent and often lethal to the embryo, mitotic aneuploidy is often self-correcting with further embryo development. NGS testing will also identify the gender of each karyotyped embryo. NGS can also be performed at lower cost than most other options such as aCGH and mCGH. Finally, it is likely that in the future, the performance time for NGS testing will speed up allowing for results to become available in time for blastocysts transferred fresh, without the need for an FET in a subsequent cycle. Given all these and other emerging benefits, NGS embryo karyotyping holds great promise for the future.
